<h2 style="font-family: 'Roboto', sans-serif;">What are Super-Earths?</h2>

<p>Super-Earths are intriguing exoplanets larger than Earth but smaller than Neptune, often found in the habitable zones
    of their stars. These planets, composed of rock, gas, or both, vary greatly in atmosphere and surface conditions,
    potentially supporting liquid water and life. Their prevalence in the galaxy suggests they're common, with some
    estimates indicating that a third of all exoplanets are Super-Earths. This makes them significant targets for
    research in astrobiology and the search for extraterrestrial life, given their diverse environments and greater
    detectability compared to Earth-sized planets
</p>
